That last one is especially worth calling out: adding defaults for those PKs is nice consistency, but it is not evidence of a modeling bug unless the tool layer truly assumes server-side generation.

On your proposed corrected schema

I like the spirit of it. I would edit it in these ways:

Keep

epistemic CHECK

capability CHECK

reconsidered temporal CHECK

possibly UUID defaults on secondary tables if consistent with implementation

Change

CHECK (valid_to >= valid_from) → CHECK (valid_to > valid_from)

any node_id REFERENCES nodes should be revisited because of composite PK

partial HNSW should be marked benchmark-required, not assumed

created_by_event on blobs should either be NOT NULL if you want real consistency, or omitted; “optional lineage FK” is halfway

That last point matters. Optional lineage FKs tend to encode uncertainty rather than design. If blob lineage is important, make it mandatory. If it is auxiliary, leave it out and rely on event payload.

My final verdict in one sentence

This is a high-quality systems reading with real architectural value.
It catches the important invariants, correctly identifies several missing DB constraints, and surfaces the main operational risks. The biggest thing to tighten is the interaction between composite temporal identity on nodes and all the places that casually treat node_id as if it were a simple unique FK target.

That tension is, to me, the deepest structural question in the whole model.

